Longevity and Happiness

Wentao Li, Hongyan Zheng

7/5/2021

Blog

The decade of The Tens marked a period of great international migration and travel. Whether it was in the cabin of international flights, the deck of a cruise ship, or the backseat of a minivan, travelling, adventuring and migrating defined the decade as people seek a better life for their family and children. According to the United Nations, by the end of the decade, the number of international migrant reached 272 million, with Europe and North America receiving the majority. The pursuit of material success often mirrored a pursuit of a happy, long-lasting life. This was reflected in the recent World Happiness Reports, in which Nordic countries often topped the charts in their happiness rank, the Life Ladder Rank. Therefore we conceded ourselves to the following main questions that has inquired millenniums of philosophy and religion: “Is there a possible way to maximize human life expectancy? Is happiness the key?” In the below study, we hope to examine the various socioeconomic variables that would affect both happiness and life expectancy, how geography impacts happiness and life expectancy, and whether having a high life expectancy had any relations to having a happy life, and vice versa. To analyze these possible relationships, we have asked ourselves the following questions: “Does a change in life expectancy reflect a similar change in happiness, vise versa?”, “Are these socioeconomic variables provided by the World Happiness Report related to life expectancy?”, “Which variable affects life expectancy and happiness the most?”, “Does geography have an impact on life expectation and happiness?”.

To answer these relationship and questions, we have imported, cleaned and analyzed three data sets, “The World Happiness Report” powered by data from Gallup World Poll, “Global Life Expectancy” collected from ourworldindata.org, and a data set containing all countries and their respective continents. Both “The World Happiness Report” and “Global Life Expectancy” data sets were filtered such that only statistics from 2008 to 2019 is observed, as it not only contains the full decade from 2010 to 2019, but also 2 years prior to observe the statistics prior to the start of the decade.

To discover the relationship between geography (continents) and life expectancy and subsequently happiness, we mainly utilized the built-in functions of ggplot. We separately plotted “Life Expectancy” and “Happiness” against “Year”, to show the change in life expectancy from 2008 to 2019, and separated the different values for different continents.

Here’s how life expectancy and happiness for each continent has changed over the last decade: As we can see, countries in Oceania has managed to not only be more happy but also a longer life expectancy, while countries in Africa has experienced drastically lower life expectancy and happiness, and other countries from other continents have remained somewhere in between. Moreover, we can observe that in general, all continents are seemingly improving their life expectancy, yet happiness for many continents has had drastic change In the last decade. There are a few other interesting observations in this graph, such as: South America’s drastic rise in happiness surpassing North America and Europe from 2010 to 2015 and then its subsequent fall back below the other two continents, and Africa’s strong rise in Life Expectancy which is not reflected in happiness until after 2015..

To further analyze the reason behind these changes, we look to discover the relationship between socio-economic variables and life expectancy, we utilized a linear regression model to analyze our data due to the large amount of numeric values. We were able to discover which values were significant. And through this process, we discovered that in relation to life expectancy, all other variables except “Happiness Score” and “Perception of Corruption” are relatively significant. Therefore we can conclude from this data that relatively to other variables, how a person view corruption and their happiness score has a relatively less significant impact on their life expectancy.

In fact, we can explore this further and discover which variable has the most effect on both life expectancy and worldwide happiness. Further utilizing linear models and tidy tools, we were able to discover that for both happiness and life expectancy, the variable that has the most common high impact on both life expectancy and worldwide happiness is “Social Support”.

Here is how life expectancy and happiness change in relation to social support: As we can see from the above plot, Social Support has a positive relationship with both life expectancy and happiness. And more importantly, both “Happiness” and “Life Expectancy” follows the previous established relationship with “Geography”.

This allows us to advance to the final question to our discussion. What is the relationship between happiness and life expectancy, vise versa? Are happy people more likely to live longer? And more importantly, if they are related, how does the change in one variable affect the change in another?

To answer this question, we utilized linear regression models and tidy tools to observe and validify both how “Life Expectancy” relates to “Happiness”, and how “Happiness” relates to “Life Expectancy”. The linear model allowed us to observe a significance for both relationships. We are able to conclude that since both relationships are significant, 1 unit increase in happiness meant an increase of 5.16 years in life expectancy and 1 year increase in life expectancy reflected in a 0.104 unit increase in happiness.

Here is how Life Expectancy is related to Happiness, the reverse relationship can also be observed:

In conclusion, although we expected it, we were fascinated to observe that each continent had distinct patterns in Happiness Score and Life Expectancy from 2008 to 2019, especially the rise and fall for South America’s Happiness Score. Subsequently, finding that the socioeconomic variable “Social Support” was the most impactful variable in common which was positively related to both Life Expectancy and Happiness Score was also surprising. This is because although it was not the most impactful variable for either Happiness Score or Life Expectancy, it was the second and third most impactful variables only slightly lower, while others failed to have an as significant impact on both variables. Lastly, we were excited to discover the significant positive linear relationship between Life Expectancy and Happiness Score, this tells us that although being happy may not be the whole key to longevity, it is definitely related.

Technical Analysis

Initial Questions:

The study attempts to find the relationship between Life Expectancy and Happiness Score through exploring the following questions: “Are all Social and Economic variables such as GDP, Social Support, Freedom of Choice, Healthy Life Expectancy at birth, Generosity, Perceptions of corruption, Positive affect, and Negative affect related to Life Expectancy?”, “What is the relationship between Geography (continent) and Life Expectancy?”, “What is the relationship between Geography (continent) and Happiness Score?”, “Do happy people live longer? If so, which variable affects both Life Expectancy and Happiness Score the most?”, and finally “Does a change in Life Expectancy reflect a similar change in Happiness Score?”.

In its initial stages, the study also hoped to explore the relationship between COVID-19 cases across the world and each country’s socioeconomic variables as well as global happiness. However, due to COVID-19 being a very recent event, and its long-lasting socioeconomic impacts, it was decided after consideration to exclude these questions and the data sets all together, and instead focusing on further exploring the relationship between Life Expectancy and Happiness Score. This allowed us to explore the last two questions, and further examine how both the socioeconomic variables and happiness impact Life Expectancy.

In the final stages of the project, we began to brainstorm additional questions for the project or future research and exploration. We planned to utilize predicting modelling and only a section of both given data sets to predict the relationship between Life Expectancy and Happiness Score in the future. Therefore, we established the following question: “Knowing both the Happiness Scores and Life Expectancy of all five continents from 2010 to 2019, how will Happiness Score and Life Expectancy change in 2020.” We believed this was an important question because we know that COVID-19 would create a global impact throughout 2020 and cause drastic changes. However, in the case that this event was miraculously avoided through early social distancing, quarantining and various other protective measures, would the relationship between Geography, Life Expectancy and Happiness Score still remain the same? However, we failed to pursue this question due to time constraints, but hope to pursue this question in a follow up study.

Data:

We used the following packages for our analysis:

library(readr)
library(tidyverse)
library(ggrepel)
library(tidyr)
library(tidymodels)
lifeExpectancy_world <- read_csv("lifeExpectancy_world.csv")
world_happiness_report <- read_csv("world-happiness-report.csv")
continent_country_tag <- read.csv("country-and-continent-codes-list-csv_csv.csv")

Here, we imported 3 csv files and stored them with respective names. Two of them are sourced from kaggle, and the other is datahub.io

continent_country_tag[is.na(continent_country_tag)]="NA"
  
continent_country_tag <- continent_country_tag %>% rename("Code" = Three_Letter_Country_Code)

data <- lifeExpectancy_world %>% 
  rename("Country name" = Entity) %>% 
  pivot_longer(3:72, names_to = "year", values_to = "Expectancy") %>% 
  mutate(year = as.numeric(year)) %>% 
  filter(year >= 2008) %>% 
  left_join(world_happiness_report) %>% 
  left_join(continent_country_tag, by = "Code") %>% 
  na.omit() %>%
  mutate(year = as.Date(as.character(year), format = "%Y"))

Secondly, we took out all the variables with P-value larger than 5% from the model and named it as fit_significant. Since the p-value of the Anova test is greater than 5%; therefore, the two models are adequate, we choose the second model which contains less variables. The p-values of all the variables are smaller than 5% in the second model support our decision as well. A significant variable means that it brings in true impact to the response variable.

plot(fit_significant, which = 2)

Finally, we check the model assumption with QQ plot, and it shows that the normality assumption is valid since the majority of residuals are along with the diagonal dash line.

Question 2

Question: What is the relationship between continents and Life Expectancy?

Initial Results:

data %>% 
  select(Expectancy, Continent_Name, `year`) %>% 
  group_by(Continent_Name) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(year, Expectancy ,color = Continent_Name)) + 
  geom_smooth() +
  ggtitle("Relationship Between Geography and Life Expectancy") +
  labs(color = "Continent Name") +
  xlab("Year") +
  ylab("Life Expectancy")

First, we selected the variables that we interested in, and then grouped by the continents’ name. Secondly, we demonstrated the relationship with ggplot() function. Since we are interested in Life Expectancy, which is a continuous variable, and continents, which is a categorical variable, we also included a continuous variable, year, in order to make a reasonable plot. Based on the observation, there is definitely a relationship as different continents have drastically different life expectancy rates. Oceania has the highest life expectancy, followed by Europe, South America, North America, Asia and then subsequently Africa over time. We can also see that life expectancy for all continents have increased over time.

Question 5

Question: Does a change in Life Expectancy reflect a similar change in Happiness Score?

Initial Results:

fit1 <- lm(Expectancy ~ `Life Ladder`, data = data)
tidy(fit1)
## # A tibble: 2 x 5
##   term          estimate std.error statistic   p.value
##   <chr>            <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)      44.0      0.692      63.7 0        
## 2 `Life Ladder`     5.16     0.125      41.4 1.98e-250
plot(fit1, which = 2)

fit2 <- lm(`Life Ladder` ~ Expectancy, data = data)
tidy(fit2)
## # A tibble: 2 x 5
##   term        estimate std.error statistic   p.value
##   <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)   -2.02    0.181       -11.2 7.36e- 28
## 2 Expectancy     0.104   0.00250      41.4 1.98e-250
plot(fit2, which = 2)

Here, we built two linear regression models with Life Expectancy and Happiness Score as the response variable respectively but with only 1 exploratory variable Life Expectancy or Happiness Score. Then, we check the model assumption with QQ plot, and it shows that the normality assumption is valid since the majority of residuals are along with the diagonal dash line. Both models have p-values less than 5% for Happiness Score and Life Expectancy, meaning these two variables are significant in both models. Looking at the estimate variable, both maintain a positive relationship. To interpret the relationship, we say 1 unit increase in Happiness Score would increase 5.157532 years in Life Expectancy. Similarly, 1 unit increase in Life Expectancy would increase 0.1035215 in Happiness Score.

data %>% select(`Life Ladder`, Expectancy, Continent_Name) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(y = `Life Ladder`, x = Expectancy)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = Continent_Name)) +
  geom_smooth() +
  ggtitle("Happiness vs Life Expectancy") +
  ylab("Happiness Score") +
  xlab("Life Expectancy") +
  labs("Continent Name")

Here, we demonstrated the plot of Happiness Score against Life Expectancy. Comparing with the plot of Life Expectancy against Happiness Score in the beginning of Question 4, we noticed that they both have positive relationship. One interesting finding is that people who are expected to live longer than 82 years might have a greater chance to feel less happy than people who are expected to live less than 82 years.

Final Analysis

In conclusion, we learn that the Life Expectancy and Happiness Score have positive linear relationships; therefore, an unit increase in one could lead to an unit increase in the other even though there are some more significant variables out there. For instance, Social Support is the most significant one that impacts both variables in a positive relationship commonly; in another word, an unit increase in Social Support could lead to an unit increase in either Life Expectancy or Happiness Score. The questions were answered through creating and observing plots and linear regression models based on the given data sets. Results showed that through finding and observing the p-values of the linear models and creating Q-Q plots for checking the model assumption justify that the linear regression is a reasonable method to reach our answers.

Related Work:

https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31451635/

This study was inspired by “Optimism is associated with exceptional longevity in 2 epidemiologic cohorts of men and women”, a study conducted by numerous researchers such as Lewina O Lee, Peter James, Emily S. Zevon, etc. This research tested whether higher optimism was associated with longer life span and greater likelihood of exceptional longevity. The researchers analyzed data from two large population studies: the Nurses’ Health Study of 70,000 women, and the Veterans Affairs Normative Aging Study of 1,400 men. It also analyzed Happiness through the Life Orientation Test from the Nurses’ Health Study and the Optimism-Pessimism Scale from the Normative Aging study. The researchers found that for both men and women, higher levels of optimism were associated with a longer life span. This study inspired us as the results had shown that optimism did have a relationship with longevity. Therefore, we hoped to expand the study from optimism to general Happiness and the focus from only the United States to a more global perspective. After reading the study, we hoped to explore whether Happiness Score, in our study represented by the Life Ladder rank, is related to life expectancy.
